76561198121676772,Recommended,255280,33062362,Posted: 30 June,all,PACFAN,"1954 Alcatraz was a fun experience for me first and foremost because I'm a diehard PAC fan, but secondly because I've toured Alcatraz and San Francisco multiple times and am familiar with its history. I really enjoyed how the game captured the sights and sounds of the setting and its mosaic cultures with both authenticity and a creative twist.As a narrative, I found the story both clear and interesting playing two antiheroes, together completing their side of the puzzle to achieve the end, while allowing the user to choose different paths and times to act. The dialogue is well-done and uses beat phrases to lend to its authenticity.The art was lovely. Again, part of this comes from recongizing scenes of the city and the island and enjoying how the artists captured it well, but part of it was appreciating the way they enhanced the looks with play of light and colour. The character designs had nice variety, although I found some of the men's head shapes to be a bit strange, as if they were missing the top of their skulls. The music lent itself well to the mood and, again, sounded authentic and fitting for the time and place.Gameplay was generally good. The puzzles were clear and logical but took some thinking, which made for a good amount of challenge without becoming frustrating. Where I found the gameplay frustrating was on two accounts:1) The game froze/locked up on me on several occasions and I had to restart. I found a certain action (Joe looking at the doctor) to freeze the game repeatedly, but the other actions that led to the freeze seemed to be random/unpredictable.2) The game allows nonlinear puzzle solving, but on multiple occasions I seemed to come to a deadlock where I needed one of the characters to do something for the other, but the option to switch characters was no longer present. It would have been good to have the character warn the player that he/she needed to do x before y or otherwise not deactivate that character's accessibility.3) The above issues combined with the fact that the game does not autosave like many PAC games do these days meant I had to replay a lot of the game, as it took a while to realize I just needed to save often.In all, I was happy with the game, but found the gameplay issues reminiscent of the kinds of errors the old PAC games had that newer ones (including all of the other Daedalic games I've played) have already solved and worked into the design."
,Not Recommended,255280,24727287,"Posted: 5 August, 2016",all,Miss Stormkast,"Uninspiring, unpolished game that decided to break near the end.1954 Alcatraz is a point-and-click adventure with great art style, for the most part good voice actors, and some nice music. Unfortunately, it fails to hook you as its story and characters have potential, but you only get to scratch the surface. You'd want to get to know these people and their backgrounds better to be able to get involved and interested in their stories. Even after a few hours, I still haven't got a good reason as to why I should care for the main characters. One or two humorous dialogue options and some random bad guys out to get them doesn't really make me motivated.The main reason that I cannot recommend this game, though, is a game breaking oversight too many hours in.Near the end, there is a part where you have to switch between the characters to make one of them bring some items for the other one. However, if you trigger an event that makes the story proceed BEFORE you've brought every item needed, you'll get stuck with the other character, unable to switch to the item bringing one since the game considers their part to be done. In other words: You won't get the items needed, you can't switch character and you can't finish the game. There is absolutely no indication that this will happen and you do not get a game over. All you can do is aimlessly wander around with your active character and do nothing at all.Since the game doesn't tell you that you screwed up and obviously expects you to have done everything in the correct order before proceeding (which you possibly cannot know before you've made the mistake), I assume that this isn't on purpose but a bug that seemingly has been ignored by the developers; Take a look at the discussions page and you'll find more players running into the same problem a year before I did.Even without this bug, or whatever it should be classified as, 1954 Alcatraz is definitely not worth 19,98€. The story and character writing is too uninspired and messy, the animations are a bit clunky and there are a couple too many black and/or loading screens, often interrupting the end of the scenes. If you're a huge adventure/point-and-click fan, then you might wanna give it a chance, but look for a huge discount first."
