,Recommended,255280,20401636,"Posted: 8 January, 2016",all,supplementscene,"PLEASE Daedalic make a sequel to Alatraz. There's plenty of scope for these characters, timeframe and setting to develop....Anyway on to the review a truely beautiful drawn point and click atmopheric cinematic adventure. The music and voice acting is a perfect match for the style of the charming visuals. Christine is a a sassy pouty lead female brilliantly drawn to portray her expressions and attitude. The expressions on the characters faces are particularly good in close ups/cut scenes.I've seen criticisms of the plot and while it is a little basic and not many twists it keeps you interested and you want to see it progress. I thought the end was maybe a little rushed. There are multiple endings, which adds a little (not much) replay value. I'd like to see extra gameplay and ending for each option. I still only have half of the achievements apparently so maybe there's more replay value.Some question whether the interracial relationship element of the story could have been explored further but if this was gone into in depth you'd have an awful degree of darkness with the racism of the times. It likely becomes a controversial game and difficult to do justice to the issues at hand.Gameplay wise it's not the most challenging P&C game, although I did use a walkthrough at times. Puzzles fans maybe disapointing here I suppose. It does give a few hints too making it maybe too obvious for hardcore puzzlers. Personally I don't like spending days on 1 puzzle or needing to constantly break out the walkthrough so I liked the fact it didn't interrupt the story.It's a solid 8 or 9 out of 10 for me. I was playing this alongside Gabriel Knight and The Secret of Monkey Island. And while I wouldn't say it's better I've played more of it recently and finished it before those too. It's certainly more of a cinematic experience. If you're a hardcore puzzler this maybe not your cup of tea. I'm surprised this has so many negative reviews but maybe that's why. I much prefer this to Deponia although some may prefer the tougher puzzles that game offers. But this is purposely easier, to focus itself as a cinematic atmpospheric story. If you don't buy it now add it to your wishlist as sooner or later it'll be offer and cheap as chips. Not that you'll regret buying it at full price."
