76561197999759842,Not Recommended,255280,30350129,Posted: 5 March,all,Terry Bogard,"1954 Alcatraz is a pretty alright adventure game, as far as adventure games made past the 90's and early 00's go. The story is that you control either Joe or Christine and try to find a way for Joe to get off the island and Christine to not end up at the bottom of the bay as a result of her criminal connections.The era, dialogue, and characters are all interesting and well worth the price of admission for the game, but that's about all there is. The gameplay is very limited, much like the simplicity of Telltale titles but without anything being totally obvious. Aside from a few select choices, there's very little variation in the story. None of the puzzles are too perplexing, and work within realistic physics so no worry of chicken-pulleys here.Though, buyer beware, this game is not unlike Telltale titles in that it's buggy. I had one progress blocker where my character was stuck in a position unable to take any actions, and because it was a pseudo cutscene I couldn't pause to restart. Mind, this wasn't a crash, my character was still doing his breathing animation and the sounds were as though nothing had changed. In addition, there's a pretty widespread problem where the Steam achievements don't work, and the developer is delightfully ignoring this glaring, consistent, issue. There also doesn't seem like there'll be any patch to fix it, as I've had this title for about a year and so far nothing.In summary: The game would be good, worth about 5 bucks at the most, but only if a patch comes out that fixes most of the foreseeable bugs. Until then, this is a story you can ignore."
,Not Recommended,255280,30276673,Posted: 2 March,all,Matthew Carr,"I have to say the only reason to buy this title is if it is at least 75% off and you want to kill 5-6 hours.At full price I would have been very unhappy - Luckily my situation is as I mentioned above.It was cheap and I was bored.Personally I'm not really a fan of the '50s setting so thematically it wasn't off to a great start.If you like the 50's then it'll be fine for you, but the visuals and music were not something I particularly enjoyed.The gameplay itself is typical point and click, there's nothing groundbreaking here.mechanically I found it a bit annoying having to constantly press spacebar to bring up the interacable items - I feel that some sort of small highlight would have been both unintrusive and more intuitive.The ending... Well, that decision that comes up really shouldn't be there. It kind of robs the game of all the build up just to be presented with the question that essentially said ""Why'd you bother playing?""If you like point and click, and it's on sale - feel free to grab it.Otherwise I wouldn't bother."
